"Rödder D., Kielgast J., Lötters S.","Future potential distribution of the emerging amphibian chytrid fungus under anthropogenic climate change",2010,"Diseases of Aquatic Organisms","92","2-3",,"201","207",,,10.3354/dao02197,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78650452464&partnerID=40&md5=8665b8f27c52e614c0bc12ae3eba3a73","Zoologisches Forschungsmuseum Alexander Koenig, Adenauerallee 160, 53113 Bonn, Germany; Department of Biogeography, Trier University, Am Wissenschaftspark 25-27, 54296 Trier, Germany; Natural History Museum of Denmark, Zoological Museum, Universitetsparken 15, 2100 Copenhagen, Denmark","Rödder, D., Zoologisches Forschungsmuseum Alexander Koenig, Adenauerallee 160, 53113 Bonn, Germany, Department of Biogeography, Trier University, Am Wissenschaftspark 25-27, 54296 Trier, Germany; Kielgast, J., Natural History Museum of Denmark, Zoological Museum, Universitetsparken 15, 2100 Copenhagen, Denmark; Lötters, S., Department of Biogeography, Trier University, Am Wissenschaftspark 25-27, 54296 Trier, Germany","Anthropogenic climate change poses a major threat to global biodiversity with a potential to alter biological interactions at all spatial scales. Amphibians are the most threatened vertebrates and have been subject to increasing conservation attention over the past decade. A particular concern is the pandemic emergence of the parasitic chytrid fungus Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis, which has been identified as the cause of extremely rapid large-scale declines and species extinctions. Experimental and observational studies have demonstrated that the host-pathogen system is strongly influenced by climatic parameters and thereby potentially affected by climate change. Herein we project a species distribution model of the pathogen onto future climatic scenarios generated by the IPCC to examine their potential implications on the pandemic. Results suggest that predicted anthropogenic climate change may reduce the geographic range of B. dendrobatidis and its potential influence on amphibian biodiversity. © Inter-Research 2010.","Amphibia; Anthropogenic future climate change; Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis; Bioclimate; Chytridiomycosis; Global warming; Maxent; Species distribution model","amphibian; anthropogenic effect; disease control; disease spread; fungus; geographical distribution; global warming; host-pathogen interaction; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; zoogeography; Amphibia; animal; animal disease; article; biodiversity; Chytridiomycetes; climate change; host pathogen interaction; human activities; microbiology; mycosis; physiology; time; Amphibians; Animals; Biodiversity; Chytridiomycota; Climate Change; Host-Pathogen Interactions; Human Activities; Mycoses; Time Factors; Amphibia; Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis; Fungi; Vertebrata",,,,,,"Alford, R.A., Bradfield, K.S., Richards, S.J., Ecology: Global warming and amphibian losses (2007) Nature, 447, pp. E3-E4; Andre, S.E., Parker, J., Briggs, C.J., Effect of temperature on host response to Batrachochytrium dendrobatidis infection in the mountain yellow-legged frog (Rana muscosa) (2008) J Wildl Dis, 44, pp. 716-720; Araújo, M.B., New, M., Ensemble forecasting of species distributions (2007) Trends Ecol Evol, 22, pp. 42-47; Araújo, M.B., Cabeza, M., Thullier, W., Hannah, L., Williams, P.H., Would climate change drive species out of reserves? An assessment of existing reserve-selection methods (2004) Glob Change Biol, 10, pp. 1618-1626; Bielby, J., Cooper, N., Cunningham, A.A., Garner, T.W.J., Purvis, A., Predicting susceptibility to future declines in the world's frogs (2008) Conserv Lett, 1, pp. 82-90; Bosch, J., Carrascal, L.M., Duran, L., Walker, S., Fisher, M.C., Climate change and outbreaks of amphibian chytridiomycosis in a montane area of Central Spain; is there a link? (2007) Proc R Soc Lond B Biol Sci, 274, pp. 253-260; Busby, J.R., BIOCLIM: A bioclimatic analysis and prediction system (1991) Nature Conservation: Cost Effecti